javascript.explanation:
A programming language is said to have First-class functions when functions in that language are treated like any other variable. 
For example, in such a language, a function can be: 
1)passed as an argument to other functions; 
2)returned by another function; 
3)assigned as a value to a variable.

JavaScript is suitable for functional programming because it supports the concept of higher-order functions. 
Functional programming is an approach to programming, where functions can be passed to other functions as parameters or can be used as values returned by other functions. 
In JavaScript functions that work with other functions (accept them as arguments or return them as results) are called Higher-order functions. 
In other words, Higher-order functions (HOFs) can do at least one of the following: 
1)Accept other functions as arguments; 
2) Return a function as a result. 
This ability allows developers to write clean, reusable, and expressive code. 
These are the most popular higher order functions in JavaScript: 
1. Array.prototype.map(); 
2. Array.prototype.filter(); 
3. Array.prototype.reduce(); 
4. Array.prototype.forEach(); 
5. Array.prototype.some(); 
6. Array.prototype.every()

The setTimeout() method is used to execute a function or evaluate an expression after a specified number of milliseconds. 
The setTimeout() method returns an ID value that can be used to cancel the timeout using the clearTimeout() method. 
Syntax: setTimeout(function, milliseconds, param1, param2, ...) 
function - the function to be executed; 
milliseconds - the number of milliseconds to wait before executing the code; 
param1, param2, ... - additional parameters to pass to the function.

