The Object.is() static method determines whether two values are the same value. 
Two values are the same if one of the following holds: 
both ‚Äùundefined‚Äù; 
both ‚Äùnull‚Äù; 
both ‚Äùtrue‚Äù or both ‚Äùfalse‚Äù; 
both strings of the same length with the same characters in the same order; 
both the same object (meaning both values reference the same object in memory); 
both ‚ÄùBigInts‚Äù with the same numeric value; 
both ‚Äùsymbols‚Äù that reference the same symbol value; 
both numbers and both +0 or both -0 or both ‚ÄùNaN‚Äù or both non-zero, not NaN, and have the same value. 
Object.is() is not equivalent to the ‚Äô‚Äô==‚Äô‚Äô operator. The ‚Äô‚Äô==‚Äô‚Äô operator applies various coercions to both sides (if they are not the same Type) before testing for equality. 
Object.is() does not coerce either value. 
Object.is() is also not equivalent to the ‚Äô‚Äô===‚Äô‚Äô operator. 
The only difference between Object.is() and ‚Äô‚Äô===‚Äô‚Äô is in their treatment of signed zeros and NaN values. 
The ‚Äô‚Äô===‚Äô‚Äô operator (and the ‚Äô‚Äô==‚Äô‚Äô operator) treats the number values ‚Äô‚Äô-0‚Äù and ‚Äô‚Äô+0‚Äù as equal, but treats NaN as not equal to each other. 
In contrast: Object.is(+0, -0) would give false. 
Object.is(NaN, 0 / 0) would give true.

